# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: tetens-equation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:tetens-equation/antoine-equation] The **Antoine equation** is a class of semi-empirical correlations describing the relation between vapor pressure and temperature for pure substances.
[src:tetens-equation/antoine-equation] The equation was presented in 1888 by the French engineer Louis Charles Antoine (1825–1897).
[src:tetens-equation/antoine-equation] The Antoine equation is $\log _{10}p=A-{\frac {B}{C+T}},$ where p is the vapor pressure, T is temperature (in °C or in K according to the value of C), and A, B and C are component-specific constants.
[src:tetens-equation/antoine-equation] The simplified form with C set to zero, $\log _{10}p=A-{\frac {B}{T}},$ is the **August equation**, after the German physicist Ernst Ferdinand August (1795–1870).
[src:tetens-equation/antoine-equation] The August equation describes a linear relation between the logarithm of the pressure and the reciprocal temperature.
[src:tetens-equation/antoine-equation] This assumes a temperature-independent heat of vaporization.
[src:tetens-equation/antoine-equation] The Antoine equation allows an improved, but still inexact description of the change of the heat of vaporization with the temperature.
[src:tetens-equation/antoine-equation] Usually, the Antoine equation cannot be used to describe the entire saturated vapour pressure curve from the triple point to the critical point, because it is not flexible enough.
[src:tetens-equation/antoine-equation] Therefore, multiple parameter sets for a single component are commonly used.
[src:tetens-equation/antoine-equation] A low-pressure parameter set is used to describe the vapour pressure curve up to the normal boiling point and the second set of parameters is used for the range from the normal boiling point to the critical point.
[src:tetens-equation/antoine-equation] The normal boiling point of ethanol is *T*B = 78.32 °C.
[src:tetens-equation/antoine-equation] This example shows a severe problem caused by using two different sets of coefficients.
[src:tetens-equation/antoine-equation] The described vapor pressure is not continuous—at the normal boiling point the two sets give different results.
[src:tetens-equation/antoine-equation] This causes severe problems for computational techniques which rely on a continuous vapor pressure curve.
[src:tetens-equation/antoine-equation] Two solutions are possible: The first approach uses a single Antoine parameter set over a larger temperature range and accepts the increased deviation between calculated and real vapor pressures.
[src:tetens-equation/antoine-equation] A variant of this single set approach is using a special parameter set fitted for the examined temperature range.
[src:tetens-equation/antoine-equation] The second solution is switching to another vapor pressure equation with more than three parameters.
[src:tetens-equation/antoine-equation] Commonly used are simple extensions of the Antoine equation (see below) and the equations of DIPPR or Wagner.
[src:tetens-equation/antoine-equation] The coefficients of Antoine's equation are normally given in **mmHg**—even today where the SI is recommended and pascals are preferred.
[src:tetens-equation/antoine-equation] The usage of the pre-SI units has only historic reasons and originates directly from Antoine's original publication.
[src:tetens-equation/antoine-equation] It is, however, easy to convert the parameters to different pressure and temperature units.
[src:tetens-equation/antoine-equation] For switching from degrees Celsius to kelvins, it is sufficient to subtract 273.15 from the *C* parameter.
[src:tetens-equation/antoine-equation] A similarly simple transformation can be used if the common logarithm should be replaced by the natural logarithm.
[src:tetens-equation/antoine-equation] It is sufficient to multiply the *A* and *B* parameters by ln(10) = 2.302585.
[src:tetens-equation/antoine-equation] The additional parameters increase the flexibility of the equation and allow the description of the entire vapor pressure curve.
[src:tetens-equation/antoine-equation] The extended equation forms can be reduced to the original form by setting the additional parameters *D*, *E* and *F* to 0.
[src:tetens-equation/antoine-equation] A further difference is that the extended equations use the *e* as base for the exponential function and the natural logarithm.
[src:tetens-equation/antoine-equation] The fundamental structure of the equation is based on the van der Waals equation and builds upon the findings of Wall, and Gutmann et al., who reformulated it into the Antoine equation.
[src:tetens-equation/antoine-equation] The proposed equation demonstrates improved accuracy compared to the Lee–Kesler method.
[src:tetens-equation/arden-buck-equation] The **Arden Buck equations** are a group of empirical correlations that relate the saturation vapor pressure to temperature for moist air.
[src:tetens-equation/arden-buck-equation] The curve fits have been optimized for more accuracy than the Goff–Gratch equation in the range −80 to 50 °C (−112 to 122 °F).
[src:tetens-equation/arden-buck-equation] A set of several equations were developed, each of which is applicable in a different situation.
[src:tetens-equation/arden-buck-equation] Buck (1981) also lists enhancement factors for a temperature range of −80 to 50 °C (−112 to 122 °F) at pressures of 1,000 mb, 500 mb, and 250 mb.
[src:tetens-equation/arden-buck-equation] These coefficients are listed in the table below.
[src:tetens-equation/august-roche-magnus] The **Clausius–Clapeyron relation**, in chemical thermodynamics, specifies the temperature dependence of pressure, most importantly vapor pressure, at a discontinuous phase transition between two phases of matter of a single constituent.
[src:tetens-equation/august-roche-magnus] It is named after Rudolf Clausius and Benoît Paul Émile Clapeyron.
[src:tetens-equation/august-roche-magnus] However, this relation was in fact originally derived by Sadi Carnot in his *Reflections on the Motive Power of Fire*, which was published in 1824 but largely ignored until it was rediscovered by Clausius, Clapeyron, and Lord Kelvin decades later.
[src:tetens-equation/august-roche-magnus] Kelvin and his brother James Thomson confirmed the relation experimentally in 1849–50, and it was historically important as a very early successful application of theoretical thermodynamics.
[src:tetens-equation/august-roche-magnus] Its relevance to meteorology and climatology is the increase of the water-holding capacity of the atmosphere by about 7% for every 1 °C (1.8 °F) rise in temperature.
[src:tetens-equation/august-roche-magnus] On a pressure–temperature (*P*–*T*) diagram, for any phase change the line separating the two phases is known as the coexistence curve.
[src:tetens-equation/august-roche-magnus] The Clapeyron relation gives the slope of the tangents to this curve.
[src:tetens-equation/august-roche-magnus] Alternatively, the specific values may be used instead of the molar ones.
[src:tetens-equation/august-roche-magnus] The Clausius–Clapeyron equation applies to vaporization of liquids where vapor follows ideal gas law using the ideal gas constant R and liquid volume is neglected as being much smaller than vapor volume *V*.
[src:tetens-equation/august-roche-magnus] It is often used to calculate vapor pressure of a liquid.
[src:tetens-equation/august-roche-magnus] where *N* is the amount of substance and *n* is the number density.
[src:tetens-equation/august-roche-magnus] The equation expresses this in a more convenient form just in terms of the latent heat, for moderate temperatures and pressures.
[src:tetens-equation/august-roche-magnus] Suppose two phases, $\alpha$ and $\beta$ , are in contact and at equilibrium with each other.
[src:tetens-equation/august-roche-magnus] from which the derivation of the Clapeyron equation continues as in the previous section.
[src:tetens-equation/august-roche-magnus] where P is the pressure, R is the specific gas constant, and T is the temperature.
[src:tetens-equation/august-roche-magnus] Instead of the specific, corresponding molar values (i.e.
[src:tetens-equation/august-roche-magnus] L in kJ/mol and R = 8.31 J/(mol⋅K)) may also be used.
[src:tetens-equation/august-roche-magnus] Let $(P_{1},T_{1})$ and $(P_{2},T_{2})$ be any two points along the coexistence curve between two phases $\alpha$ and $\beta$ .
[src:tetens-equation/august-roche-magnus] In general, L varies between any two such points, as a function of temperature.
[src:tetens-equation/august-roche-magnus] These last equations are useful because they relate equilibrium or saturation vapor pressure and temperature to the latent heat of the phase change *without* requiring specific-volume data.
[src:tetens-equation/august-roche-magnus] In the original work by Clapeyron, the following argument is advanced.
[src:tetens-equation/august-roche-magnus] Clapeyron considered a Carnot process of saturated water vapor with horizontal isobars.
[src:tetens-equation/august-roche-magnus] As the pressure is a function of temperature alone, the isobars are also isotherms.
[src:tetens-equation/august-roche-magnus] The ratio $W/Q$ is the efficiency of the Carnot engine, $\mathrm {d} T/T$ .
[src:tetens-equation/august-roche-magnus] Substituting and rearranging gives ${\frac {\mathrm {d} p}{\mathrm {d} T}}={\frac {L}{T(v''-v')}},$ where lowercase $v''-v'$ denotes the change in *specific volume* during the transition.
[src:tetens-equation/august-roche-magnus] For a liquid–gas transition, L is the molar latent heat (or molar enthalpy) of vaporization; for a solid–gas transition, L is the molar latent heat of sublimation.
[src:tetens-equation/august-roche-magnus] If the latent heat is known, then knowledge of one point on the coexistence curve, for instance (1 bar, 373 K) for water, determines the rest of the curve.
[src:tetens-equation/august-roche-magnus] Conversely, the relationship between $\ln P$ and $1/T$ is linear, and so linear regression is used to estimate the latent heat.
[src:tetens-equation/august-roche-magnus] Atmospheric water vapor drives many important meteorologic phenomena (notably, precipitation), motivating interest in its dynamics.
[src:tetens-equation/august-roche-magnus] The temperature dependence of the latent heat ${\textstyle L_{\text{v}}(T)}$ can be neglected in this application.
[src:tetens-equation/august-roche-magnus] The above formula is also sometimes called the *Magnus* or *Magnus–Tetens* approximation, though this attribution is historically inaccurate; see also the discussion of the accuracy of different approximating formulae for saturation vapour pressure of water.
[src:tetens-equation/august-roche-magnus] Under typical atmospheric conditions, the denominator in the exponent ${\textstyle T+243.04}$ depends weakly on ${\textstyle T}$ .
[src:tetens-equation/august-roche-magnus] Therefore, the August–Roche–Magnus formula implies that saturation vapor pressure changes approximately exponentially with temperature under typical atmospheric conditions, and hence the water-holding capacity of the atmosphere increases by about 7% for every 1 °C rise in temperature.
[src:tetens-equation/august-roche-magnus] One of the uses of this equation is to determine if a phase transition will occur in a given situation.
[src:tetens-equation/august-roche-magnus] Consider the question of how much pressure is needed to melt ice at a temperature ${\Delta T}$ below 0 °C.
[src:tetens-equation/august-roche-magnus] Note that water is unusual in that its change in volume upon melting is negative.
[src:tetens-equation/august-roche-magnus] To provide a rough example of how much pressure this is, to melt ice at −7 °C (the temperature many ice skating rinks are set at) would require balancing a small car on an area around 1cm2.
[src:tetens-equation/august-roche-magnus] This shows that ice skating cannot be simply explained by pressure-caused melting point depression, and in fact the mechanism is quite complex.
[src:tetens-equation/august-roche-magnus] While the Clausius–Clapeyron relation gives the slope of the coexistence curve, it does not provide any information about its curvature or second derivative.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] The **degree Celsius** is the unit of temperature on the **Celsius temperature scale** (originally known as the **centigrade scale** in English), one of two temperature scales used in the International System of Units (SI), the other being the closely related Kelvin scale.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] The degree Celsius (symbol: **°C**) can refer to a specific point on the Celsius temperature scale or to a difference or range between two temperatures.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] It is named after the Swedish astronomer Anders Celsius (1701–1744), who proposed the first version of it in 1742.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] The unit was called *centigrade* in several languages (from the Latin *centum*, which means 100, and *gradus*, which means steps) for many years.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] In 1948, the International Committee for Weights and Measures renamed it to honor Celsius and also to remove confusion with the term for one hundredth of a gradian in some languages.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] Most countries use this scale, with the exception of the United States, some island territories, and Liberia, where the Fahrenheit scale is still used.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] Throughout the 19th and the first half of the 20th centuries, the scale was based on 0 °C for the freezing point of water and 100 °C for the boiling point of water at 1 atm pressure.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] Between 1954 and 2019, the precise definitions of the unit *degree Celsius* and the Celsius temperature scale used absolute zero and the temperature of the triple point of water.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] Since 2007, the Celsius temperature scale has been defined in terms of the kelvin, the SI base unit of thermodynamic temperature (symbol: K).
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] Absolute zero, the lowest temperature, is now defined as being exactly 0 K and −273.15 °C.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] In 1742, Swedish astronomer Anders Celsius (1701–1744) created a temperature scale that was the reverse of the scale now known as "Celsius": 0 represented the boiling point of water, while 100 represented the freezing point of water.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] In his paper *Observations of two persistent degrees on a thermometer*, he recounted his experiments showing that the melting point of ice is essentially unaffected by pressure.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] He also determined with remarkable precision how the boiling point of water varied as a function of atmospheric pressure.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] He proposed that the zero point of his temperature scale, being the boiling point, would be calibrated at the mean barometric pressure at mean sea level.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] This pressure is known as one standard atmosphere.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] The BIPM's 10th General Conference on Weights and Measures (CGPM) in 1954 defined one standard atmosphere to equal precisely 1,013,250 dynes per square centimeter (101.325 kPa).
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] In 1743, the French physicist Jean-Pierre Christin, permanent secretary of the Academy of Lyon, inverted the Celsius temperature scale so that 0 represented the freezing point of water and 100 represented the boiling point of water.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] Some credit Christin for independently inventing the reverse of Celsius's original scale, while others believe Christin merely reversed Celsius's scale.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] On 19 May 1743 he published the design of a mercury thermometer, the "Thermometer of Lyon" built by the craftsman Pierre Casati that used this scale.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] In 1744, coincident with the death of Anders Celsius, the Swedish botanist Carl Linnaeus (1707–1778) reversed Celsius's scale.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] His custom-made "Linnaeus-thermometer", for use in his greenhouses, was made by Daniel Ekström, Sweden's leading maker of scientific instruments at the time, whose workshop was located in the basement of the Stockholm observatory.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] The first known Swedish document reporting temperatures in this modern "forward" Celsius temperature scale is the paper *Hortus Upsaliensis* dated 16 December 1745 that Linnaeus wrote to a student of his, Samuel Nauclér.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] Since the 19th century, the scientific and thermometry communities worldwide have used the phrase "centigrade scale" and temperatures were often reported simply as "degrees" or, when greater specificity was desired, as "degrees centigrade", with the symbol °C.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] In the French language, the term *centigrade* also means one hundredth of a gradian, when used for angular measurement.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] The term *centesimal degree* was later introduced for temperatures but was also problematic, as it means gradian (one hundredth of a right angle) in the French and Spanish languages.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] The risk of confusion between temperature and angular measurement was eliminated in 1948 when the 9th meeting of the General Conference on Weights and Measures and the Comité International des Poids et Mesures (CIPM) formally adopted "degree Celsius" for temperature.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] While "Celsius" is commonly used in scientific work, "centigrade" is still used in French and English-speaking countries, especially in informal contexts.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] The frequency of the usage of "centigrade" has declined over time.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] Due to metrication in Australia, after 1 September 1972 weather reports in the country were exclusively given in Celsius.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] In the United Kingdom, it was not until February 1985 that forecasts by BBC Weather switched from "centigrade" to "Celsius".
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] All phase transitions are at standard atmosphere.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] Figures are either by definition, or approximated from empirical measurements.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] The "degree Celsius" has been the only SI unit whose full unit name contains an uppercase letter since 1967, when the SI base unit for temperature became the kelvin, replacing the capitalized term *degrees Kelvin*.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] The general rule of the International Bureau of Weights and Measures (BIPM) is that the numerical value always precedes the unit, and a space is always used to separate the unit from the number, e.g.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] The only exceptions to this rule are for the unit symbols for degree, minute, and second for plane angle (°, ′, and ″, respectively), for which no space is left between the numerical value and the unit symbol.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] Other languages, and various publishing houses, may follow different typographical rules.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] Unicode provides the Celsius symbol at code point U+2103 ℃ DEGREE CELSIUS.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] However, this is a compatibility character provided for roundtrip compatibility with legacy encodings.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] It easily allows correct rendering for vertically written East Asian scripts, such as Chinese.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] The Unicode standard explicitly discourages the use of this character: "In normal use, it is better to represent degrees Celsius '°C' with a sequence of U+00B0 ° DEGREE SIGN + U+0043 C LATIN CAPITAL LETTER C, rather than U+2103 ℃ DEGREE CELSIUS.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] The degree Celsius is subject to the same rules as the kelvin with regard to the use of its unit name and symbol.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] Thus, besides expressing specific temperatures along its scale (e.g.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] "Gallium melts at 29.7646 °C" and "The temperature outside is 23 degrees Celsius"), the degree Celsius is also suitable for expressing temperature *intervals*: differences between temperatures or their uncertainties (e.g.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] "The output of the heat exchanger is hotter by 40 degrees Celsius", and "Our standard uncertainty is ±3 °C").
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] Because of this dual usage, one must not rely upon the unit name or its symbol to denote that a quantity is a temperature interval; it must be unambiguous through context or explicit statement that the quantity is an interval.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] This is sometimes solved by using the symbol °C (pronounced "degrees Celsius") for a temperature, and C° (pronounced "Celsius degrees") for a temperature interval, although this usage is non-standard.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] Another way to express the same is "40 °C ± 3 K", which can be commonly found in literature.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] Celsius measurement follows an interval system but not a ratio system; and it follows a relative scale not an absolute scale.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] For example, an object at 20 °C does not have twice the energy of when it is 10 °C; and 0 °C is not the lowest Celsius value.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] Thus, degrees Celsius is a useful interval measurement but does not possess the characteristics of ratio measures like weight or distance.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] In science and in engineering, the Celsius and Kelvin scales are often used in combination in close contexts, e.g.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] "a measured value was 0.01023 °C with an uncertainty of 70 μK".
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] This practice is permissible because the magnitude of the degree Celsius is equal to that of the kelvin.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] Notwithstanding the official endorsement provided by decision no.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] The melting and boiling points of water are no longer part of the definition of the Celsius temperature scale.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] In 1948, the definition was changed to use the triple point of water.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] In 2005, the definition was further refined to use water with precisely defined isotopic composition (VSMOW) for the triple point.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] In 2019, the definition was changed to use the Boltzmann constant, completely decoupling the definition of the kelvin from the properties of water.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] Each of these formal definitions left the numerical values of the Celsius temperature scale identical to the prior definition to within the limits of accuracy of the metrology of the time.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] When the melting and boiling points of water ceased being part of the definition, they became measured quantities instead.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] In 1948 when the 9th General Conference on Weights and Measures (CGPM) in Resolution 3 first considered using the triple point of water as a defining point, the triple point was so close to being 0.01 °C greater than water's known melting point, it was simply defined as precisely 0.01 °C.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] However, later measurements showed that the difference between the triple and melting points of VSMOW is actually very slightly (< 0.001 °C) greater than 0.01 °C.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] Thus, the actual melting point of ice is very slightly (less than a thousandth of a degree) below 0 °C.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] Also, defining water's triple point at 273.16 K precisely defined the magnitude of each 1 °C increment in terms of the absolute thermodynamic temperature scale (referencing absolute zero).
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] Now decoupled from the actual boiling point of water, the value "100 °C" is hotter than 0 °C – in absolute terms – by a factor of *exactly* ⁠373.15/273.15⁠ (approximately 36.61% thermodynamically hotter).
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] When adhering *strictly* to the two-point definition for calibration, the boiling point of VSMOW under one standard atmosphere of pressure was actually 373.1339 K (99.9839 °C).
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] When calibrated to ITS-90 (a calibration standard comprising many definition points and commonly used for high-precision instrumentation), the boiling point of VSMOW was slightly less, about 99.974 °C.
[src:tetens-equation/celsius] For example, an altitude change of only 28 cm (11 in) causes the boiling point to change by one millikelvin.
[src:tetens-equation/goff-gratch-equation] The **Goff–Gratch equation** is one (arguably the first reliable in history) amongst many experimental correlations proposed to estimate the saturation water vapor pressure at a given temperature.
[src:tetens-equation/goff-gratch-equation] Another similar equation based on more recent data is the Arden Buck equation.
[src:tetens-equation/goff-gratch-equation] This equation is named after the authors of the original scientific article who described how to calculate the saturation water vapor pressure above a flat free water surface as a function of temperature (Goff and Gratch, 1946).
[src:tetens-equation/goff-gratch-equation] Goff (1957) later revised his formula, and the latter was recommended for use by the World Meteorological Organization in 1988, with further corrections in 2000.
[src:tetens-equation/goff-gratch-equation] The current 2015 edition of the WMO Technical Regulations (WMO-No.
[src:tetens-equation/goff-gratch-equation] 49) however states in Volume 1, Part III, Section 1.2.1, that any formula or constant given in the Guide to Meteorological Instruments and Methods of Observation a.k.a.
[src:tetens-equation/goff-gratch-equation] 8) shall be used, and this document only contains the much simpler Magnus formula (Annex 4.B. – Formulae for the computation of measures of humidity).
[src:tetens-equation/kilopascal] The **pascal** (symbol: **Pa**) is the unit of pressure in the International System of Units (SI).
[src:tetens-equation/kilopascal] It is also used to quantify internal pressure, stress, Young's modulus, and ultimate tensile strength.
[src:tetens-equation/kilopascal] The unit, named after Blaise Pascal, is an SI coherent derived unit defined as one newton per square metre (N/m2).
[src:tetens-equation/kilopascal] It is also equivalent to 10 barye (10 Ba) in the CGS system.
[src:tetens-equation/kilopascal] Common multiple units of the pascal are the hectopascal (1 hPa = 100 Pa), which is equal to one millibar, and the kilopascal (1 kPa = 1,000 Pa), which is equal to one centibar.
[src:tetens-equation/kilopascal] The unit of measurement called *standard atmosphere* (atm) is defined as 101325 Pa.
[src:tetens-equation/kilopascal] Meteorological observations typically report atmospheric pressure in hectopascals per the recommendation of the World Meteorological Organization, thus a standard atmosphere or typical sea-level air pressure is about 1,013 hPa.
[src:tetens-equation/kilopascal] Reports in the United States typically use inches of mercury or millibars (hectopascals).
[src:tetens-equation/kilopascal] In Canada, these reports are given in kilopascals.
[src:tetens-equation/kilopascal] The unit is named after Blaise Pascal, noted for his contributions to hydrodynamics and hydrostatics, and experiments with a barometer.
[src:tetens-equation/kilopascal] The name *pascal* was adopted for the SI unit newton per square metre (N/m2) by the 14th General Conference on Weights and Measures in 1971.
[src:tetens-equation/kilopascal] where N is the newton, m is the metre, kg is the kilogram, s is the second, and J is the joule.
[src:tetens-equation/kilopascal] One pascal is the pressure exerted by a force of one newton perpendicularly upon an area of one square metre.
[src:tetens-equation/kilopascal] The unit of measurement called an atmosphere or a standard atmosphere (atm) is 101325 Pa (101.325 kPa).
[src:tetens-equation/kilopascal] This value is often used as a reference pressure and specified as such in some national and international standards, such as the International Organization for Standardization's ISO 2787 (pneumatic tools and compressors), ISO 2533 (aerospace) and ISO 5024 (petroleum).
[src:tetens-equation/kilopascal] In contrast, International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC) recommends the use of 100 kPa as a standard pressure when reporting the properties of substances.
[src:tetens-equation/kilopascal] Unicode has dedicated code-points U+33A9 ㎩ SQUARE PA and U+33AA ㎪ SQUARE KPA in the CJK Compatibility block, but these exist only for backward-compatibility with some older ideographic character-sets and are therefore deprecated.
[src:tetens-equation/kilopascal] The pascal (Pa) or kilopascal (kPa) as a unit of pressure measurement is widely used throughout the world and has largely replaced the pounds per square inch (psi) unit, except in some countries that still use the imperial measurement system or the US customary system, including the United States.
[src:tetens-equation/kilopascal] Geophysicists use the gigapascal (GPa) in measuring or calculating tectonic stresses and pressures within the Earth.
[src:tetens-equation/kilopascal] Medical elastography measures tissue stiffness non-invasively with ultrasound or magnetic resonance imaging, and often displays the Young's modulus or shear modulus of tissue in kilopascals.
[src:tetens-equation/kilopascal] In materials science and engineering, the pascal measures the stiffness, tensile strength and compressive strength of materials.
[src:tetens-equation/kilopascal] In engineering the megapascal (MPa) is the preferred unit for these uses, because the pascal represents a very small quantity.
[src:tetens-equation/kilopascal] The pascal is also equivalent to the SI unit of energy density, the joule per cubic metre.
[src:tetens-equation/kilopascal] This applies not only to the thermodynamics of pressurised gases, but also to the energy density of electric, magnetic, and gravitational fields.
[src:tetens-equation/kilopascal] The pascal is used to measure sound pressure.
[src:tetens-equation/kilopascal] Loudness is the subjective experience of sound pressure and is measured as a sound pressure level (SPL) on a logarithmic scale of the sound pressure relative to some reference pressure.
[src:tetens-equation/kilopascal] For sound in air, a pressure of 20 μPa is considered to be at the threshold of hearing for humans and is a common reference pressure, so that its SPL is zero.
[src:tetens-equation/kilopascal] The airtightness of buildings is measured at 50 Pa.
[src:tetens-equation/kilopascal] In medicine, blood pressure is measured in millimeters of mercury (mmHg, very close to one Torr).
[src:tetens-equation/kilopascal] The normal adult blood pressure is less than 120 mmHg systolic BP (SBP) and less than 80 mmHg diastolic BP (DBP).
[src:tetens-equation/kilopascal] Convert mmHg to SI units as follows: 1 mmHg = 0.13332 kPa.
[src:tetens-equation/kilopascal] Hence the normal blood pressure in SI units is less than 16.0 kPa SBP and less than 10.7 kPa DBP.
[src:tetens-equation/kilopascal] These values are similar to the pressure of water column of average human height; so pressure has to be measured on arm roughly at the level of the heart.
[src:tetens-equation/kilopascal] The units of atmospheric pressure commonly used in meteorology were formerly the bar (100000 Pa), which is close to the average air pressure on Earth, and the millibar.
[src:tetens-equation/kilopascal] Since the introduction of SI units, meteorologists generally measure atmospheric pressure in hectopascals (hPa), equal to 100 pascals or 1 millibar.
[src:tetens-equation/kilopascal] Exceptions include Canada, which uses kilopascals (kPa).
[src:tetens-equation/kilopascal] In many other fields of science, prefixes that are a power of 1000 are preferred, which theoretically excludes hectopascal from use.
[src:tetens-equation/kilopascal] Many countries still use millibars to measure atmospheric pressure.
[src:tetens-equation/kilopascal] In practically all other fields, the kilopascal is used instead.
[src:tetens-equation/kilopascal] Decimal multiples and submultiples are formed using standard metric prefixes.
[src:tetens-equation/lee-kesler-method] The **Lee–Kesler method** allows the estimation of the saturated vapor pressure at a given temperature for all components for which the critical pressure *P*c, the critical temperature *T*c, and the acentric factor *ω* are known.
[src:tetens-equation/lee-kesler-method] The prediction error can be up to 10% for polar components and small pressures and the calculated pressure is typically too low.
[src:tetens-equation/lee-kesler-method] For pressures above 1 bar, that means, above the normal boiling point, the typical errors are below 2%.
[src:tetens-equation/lee-kesler-method] The correct result would be *P* = 101.325 kPa, the normal (atmospheric) pressure.
[src:tetens-equation/lee-kesler-method] It is important to use the same absolute units for *T* and *T*c as well as for *P* and *P*c.
[src:tetens-equation/lee-kesler-method] The unit system used (K or R for *T*) is irrelevant because of the usage of the reduced values *T*r and *P*r.
[src:tetens-equation/tetens-equation] The **Tetens equation** is an equation to calculate the saturation vapour pressure of water over liquid and ice.
[src:tetens-equation/tetens-equation] Tetens who was an early German meteorologist.
[src:tetens-equation/tetens-equation] He published his equation in 1930, and while the publication itself is rather obscure, the equation is widely known among meteorologists and climatologists because of its ease of use and relative accuracy at temperatures within the normal ranges of natural weather conditions.
[src:tetens-equation/tetens-equation] The equation is structurally identical to the August-Roche-Magnus equation, but the coefficients differ.
[src:tetens-equation/tetens-equation] where temperature T is in degrees Celsius (°C) and saturation vapor pressure P is in kilopascals (kPa).
